Making Interactive Maps With Sociomepy¶

Sociomepy is a Python package that provides a number of convenient functions, data structures, and models for manipulating socio-environmental data. Implementation-wise it is a wrapper around the GeoPandas library and is fully compatible with all data formats that geopandas accepts.

This notebook produces an interactive map of the City of Chicago that illustrates some of the initial data that the project has curated.

Loading Addresses¶

First, we will get a baseline set of addresses in the city of chicago so can establish regional boundaries.

In [1]:
from sociomepy.data import SociomeDataFrame
from sociomepy.accessors import access_by_attribute
chicago = SociomeDataFrame.from_csv('http://chicago-exposures.s3.amazonaws.com/chicago-assessments.csv', access_by_attribute('Longitude', 'Latitude'))

ACS Income¶

Let's add median household income to this dataset.

In [3]:
from sociomepy.metrics import SpatialSubdivisionFunction

income = SpatialSubdivisionFunction(acs, 'tract', 'SE_A1006_2', 'GEOID') 
chicago.add_metric_to_data(income, income')
chicago.to_mpl_inline(['income'])

ChiVes Data¶

Now, we will integrate data from the ChiVes Chicago Dataset. This gives us some of the Census Tract Level Asthma numbers based on Chives survey data.

In [4]:
chicago_chives = SociomeDataFrame.from_csv('http://chicago-exposures.s3.amazonaws.com/chicago-chives.csv', access_by_attribute('intptlon', 'intptlat'))
In [5]:
chicago_chives.data['geoid'] =  chicago_chives.data['geoid'].apply(lambda x: str(x)) #will be fixed in an updated version of the dataset
asthma = SpatialSubdivisionFunction(chicago_chives, 'tract', 'asthma_age_adj_rate', 'geoid') 
chicago.add_metric_to_data(asthma, 'asthma_age_adj_rate')
chicago.to_mpl_inline(['asthma_age_adj_rate'])

Exporting the Map¶

Next, we will export this map to create an interactive dialog. We will create aa 5% of addresses.
